    Twentieth-century linguistic work on Chinese (Chao 1968; Li and Thompson 1981; Tang 1988,1989, inter alia) has revealed the incorrectness of this traditional view.
    All notions of word, with the exception of the orthographic word, are as relevant in Chinese as they are in English, and just as is the case in other languages, a word in Chinese may correspond to one or more symbols in the orthography: ren2 'person' is a fairly uncontroversial case of a monographemic word, and 1131S zhongl-guo2 (middle country) 'China' a fairly uncontroversial case of a digraphemic w